# Step 4: Univariate Analysis
# Identify categorical and numerical columns
categorical_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
numerical_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns
In [44]:
# Plot categorical columns
for col in categorical_cols:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    data[col].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()

for col in numerical_cols:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.histplot(data[col], kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.show()

    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.boxplot(x=data[col])
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {col}')
    plt.show()

Observations for Each Visual¶

  1. Categorical Columns (Bar Plots) Sex:

There are more males than females onboard.

Embarked:

Most passengers embarked from port S (Southampton).

Cabin:

Most entries are missing for Cabin information.

  1. Numerical Columns (Histograms + Boxplots) Age:

Ages are mostly between 20 and 40 years.

Outliers exist (e.g., passengers aged 70–80).

Fare:

Most fares are low (under $100), but there are extreme high fares (outliers) up to $512.

SibSp (Siblings/Spouses aboard):

Most people traveled alone (0 siblings/spouses).

Parch (Parents/Children aboard):

Most passengers also had no parents or children with them.

Passenger Class (Pclass):

The largest group traveled in third class.

  1. Correlation Matrix (Heatmap) Fare is negatively correlated with Pclass (lower class number → higher fare).

SibSp and Parch show some positive correlation (families tend to travel together).

Survived is somewhat correlated with Pclass and Fare (higher class and fare increased survival chances).

  1. Pairplot Survivors seem to have higher fares and belong more to first class.

Age is spread similarly among survivors and non-survivors.

  1. Scatterplot (PassengerId vs Survived) No visible relationship between PassengerId and Survival (as expected, ID is just an index).

Summary of Findings¶

Category - Finding Demographics - Most passengers were young males between 20-40 years old. Travel Class - Majority traveled in 3rd class. Fares - Most fares were low, but some high outliers exist. Family - Most passengers were traveling alone. Survival - Higher survival rates were linked to higher passenger classes and fares. Data Quality - Significant missing values in Age, Cabin, and Embarked columns. Correlation - Fare and Pclass are strongly negatively correlated.
